value.value: A pulmonary hemorrhage adverse event in a newborn which results in death.

label.value: Grade 1 Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of the Newborn, AE

value.value: An adverse event in a newborn characterized by technical evidence of increased right ventricular pressures; no clinical symptoms.

label.value: Grade 2 Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of the Newborn, AE

value.value: An adverse event in a newborn characterized by increased estimated right ventricular pressures; with moderate clinical symptoms; oxygenation index less than 25; minor care changes required.

label.value: Grade 3 Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of the Newborn, AE

value.value: An adverse event in a newborn characterized by Increased estimated right ventricular pressures; with severe clinical symptoms; oxygenation index greater than 25; major care changes required (e.g. inhaled nitric oxide (iNO)).

label.value: Grade 4 Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of the Newborn, AE

value.value: A persistent pulmonary hypertension adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening respiratory and/or hemodynamic compromise; extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) required; oxygenation index greater than 40.

label.value: Grade 5 Persistent Pulmonary Hypertension of the Newborn, AE

value.value: A persistent pulmonary hypertension adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by radiological evidence of pneumothorax; no clinical signs; no care change required.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by radiological evidence of pneumothorax; minor clinical signs; minor care change required (e.g. oxygen, increased monitoring).
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by radiological evidence of pneumothorax; with clinical signs; major care change required (e.g. chest drainage).
A pneumothorax adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening respiratory and/or hemodynamic compromise (e.g. tension pneumothorax); urgent major care change required.
A pneumothorax adverse event in a newborn which results in death.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by the need for supplemental oxygen at 28 days AND breathing room air at 36 weeks postmenstrual age (PMA) in infants born less than 32 weeks' gestation; breathing room air by 56 days postnatal age in infants born greater than 32 weeks' gestation; breathing room air at discharge. Note: For conversion of oxygen administered by different modalities to fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2): see http://nicutools.org/MediCalcs/ActualO2.php3.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by the need for supplemental oxygen at 28 days AND need for 22-30% oxygen at 36 weeks postmenstrual age (PMA) in infants born less than 32 weeks' gestation; need for 22-30% oxygen by 56 days postnatal age in infants born greater than 32 weeks' gestation; need for 22-30% oxygen at discharge. Note: For conversion of oxygen administered by different modalities to fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2): see http://nicutools.org/MediCalcs/ActualO2.php3.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by the need for supplemental oxygen at 28 days AND need for greater than 30% oxygen or positive pressure at 36 weeks postmenstrual age (PMA) in infants born less than 32 weeks' gestation; need for greater than 30% oxygen or positive pressure by 56 days postnatal age in infants born greater than 32 weeks' gestation; need for greater than 30% oxygen and/or positive pressure at discharge. Note: For conversion of oxygen administered by different modalities to fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2): see http://nicutools.org/MediCalcs/ActualO2.php3.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by the need for supplemental oxygen at 28 days AND need for greater than 30% oxygen AND positive pressure at 36 weeks postmenstrual age (PMA) in infants born less than 32 weeks' gestation; need for greater than 30% oxygen AND positive pressure by 56 days postnatal age in infants born greater than 32 weeks' gestation; need for greater than 30% oxygen AND positive pressure at discharge. Note: For conversion of oxygen administered by different modalities to fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2): see http://nicutools.org/MediCalcs/ActualO2.php3.
A bronchopulmonary dysplasia adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by confirmed necrotizing enterocolitis; major care change indicated (e.g. NPO, antibiotics, non-urgent surgery).

A necrotizing enterocolitis adverse event in a newborn characterized by bowel perforation (pneumoperitoneum)(modified Bell stage IIIB); shock, disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), combined respiratory and metabolic acidosis (modified Bell stage IIIA); urgent major care change indicated.
A necrotizing enterocolitis adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by an increase of 2-4 stools per day over baseline; mild increase in ostomy output compared to baseline.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by an increase of 4 - 6 stools per day over baseline; moderate increase in ostomy output compared to baseline.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by an increase of 7 stools or more per day over baseline; severe increase in ostomy output compared to baseline; signs of dehydration.
A diarrhea adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening consequences (e.g. severe dehydration).
A diarrhea adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
A form of adoptive cell transfer in which lymphocytes are isolated from a patient's tumor, grown in vitro, and then infused into the patient in combination with interleukin 2.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by an increase in vomiting over baseline, self limiting.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by a persistent increase in vomiting over baseline; no dehydration; minor changes in feeding support indicated.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by a persistent increase in vomiting over baseline; signs of dehydration; major changes in feeding support indicated (e.g. change to total parenteral nutrition (TPN) or gavage).
A vomiting adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening consequences (e. g. severe dehydration).
A vomiting adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by mild feeding intolerance (e.g. increased gastric residual volume or abdominal distension); without discomfort; no change in care indicated.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by moderate feeding intolerance; resulting in minor discomfort or alteration of drinking behavior; minor care changes indicated (e.g. feeds withheld).
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by severe feeding intolerance; requiring major changes in feeding support indicated (e.g. change to total parenteral nutrition (TPN) or gavage).
A feeding intolerance adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening consequences.
A feeding intolerance adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
Drug treatment to block the action of aromatases, thereby reducing estrogen biosynthesis.
A gastrointestinal bleeding adverse event in a newborn characterized by mild, self-limiting, bleeding; no change in care required.
A gastrointestinal bleeding adverse event in a newborn characterized by moderate bleeding; minor change in care or monitoring required.

A gastrointestinal bleeding adverse event in a newborn characterized by severe bleeding; non-life threatening hemodynamic consequences; major care change required (e.g. invasive intervention, transfusion, long term medical treatment).
A gastrointestinal bleeding adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening consequences (e.g. hemorrhagic shock); urgent major care change required.
A gastrointestinal bleeding adverse event in a newborn which results in death.

label.value: Grade 3 Neonatal Spontaneous Intestinal Perforation, AE

value.value: An adverse event in a newborn characterized by presence of spontaneous intestinal perforation (SIP), non-urgent medical stabilization and surgical intervention indicated.

label.value: Grade 4 Neonatal Spontaneous Intestinal Perforation, AE

value.value: A spontaneous intestinal perforation (SIP) adverse event in a newborn characterized by life-threatening consequences (e.g. shock, organ failure); urgent intervention indicated.

label.value: Grade 5 Neonatal Spontaneous Intestinal Perforation, AE

value.value: A spontaneous intestinal perforation (SIP) adverse event in a newborn which results in death.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by reduced number of stools or hard stools; no apparent discomfort.
An adverse event in a newborn characterized by reduced number of stools or hard stools; apparent discomfort; minor care changes indicated.
Treatment with a 5a-reductase inhibitor with the goal of suppressing the conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone.

An adverse event in a newborn characterized by reduced number of stools or hard stools; signs of obstruction; apparent discomfort or affecting feeding; major care changes indicated (e.g. long term medical treatment, enema).
